events.description: The release of trade data for Iceland for the month of January 2026, showing a significant narrowing of the trade deficit.

facts.fact_text: Iceland's trade deficit narrowed to ISK 0.3 billion in January 2026 from ISK 7.8 billion in January 2025.

evidences.evidence_text: Iceland’s trade deficit narrowed sharply to ISK 0.3 billion in January 2026 from ISK 7.8 billion in the corresponding month of the previous year.

facts.fact_text: Exports declined by 20.9% year-on-year to ISK 72.4 billion.

evidences.evidence_text: Exports declined by 20.9% year-on-year to ISK 72.4 billion

facts.fact_text: Imports fell by 26.8% to ISK 72.7 billion.

evidences.evidence_text: Imports also fell by 26.8% to ISK 72.7 billion

claims.claim_text: The narrowing of the trade deficit was primarily due to exports falling less than imports.

evidences.evidence_text: This marked the smallest trade deficit since a surplus recorded in January 2019, as exports fell less than imports.

claims.claim_text: The decline in exports was weighed down by lower shipments of manufactured goods and other products.

evidences.evidence_text: weighed down by lower shipments of manufactured goods (-36.6%) and other products (-49%).

evidence.evidence_text: Exports declined by 20.9% year-on-year to ISK 72.4 billion, weighed down by lower shipments of manufactured goods
Imports also fell by 26.8% to ISK 72.7 billion, driven by a notable drop in purchases of industrial supplies (-35.8%), fuels and lubricants (-41.2%)
